    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output="Based on the provided MD&A and financial disclosures, here is the confirmation of SpaceX's Connectivity segment revenue for Q1 2026 and the context regarding its composition:\n\n**Connectivity Segment Revenue (Q1 2026)**\nFor the three months ended March 31, 2026, SpaceX's Connectivity segment generated **$3,257 million** in revenue. This represents an increase of $782 million, or 31.6%, compared to $2,475 million in the prior year quarter (Q1 2025). \n\n**Segment Composition**\nYes, the Connectivity segment includes Starlink consumer, enterprise, and government services. Specifically, the segment generates revenue from the following:\n*   **Consumer:** Revenue is driven primarily by monthly subscription fees for broadband services (based on geographic market and download speed) and the one-time sale of Starlink Kits (inclusive of the terminal). \n*   **Enterprise:** Revenue is generated through contracts structured as a combination of subscriptions, data consumption, and capacity. This includes aviation, maritime, land mobility, and other enterprise business across various industries.\n*   **Government:** Revenue is generated via long-term contracts for Starshield, a secure satellite network designed specifically for government use. \n*   **Starlink Mobile:** The segment also includes mobile connectivity services, which are accounted for under Enterprise & Government revenue. \n\n**Q1 2026 Performance Context**\nThe 31.6% year-over-year revenue growth was driven by:\n*   **Consumer Revenue:** Increased by $656 million, driven by 104.7% growth in Starlink Subscribers. This was partially offset by a 22.9% decline in Starlink Subscriber ARPU, primarily due to international expansion and the addition of lower-priced service plans.\n*   **Enterprise & Government Revenue:** Increased by $126 million. This was driven by $209 million in growth from aviation, maritime, and other enterprise business, plus $85 million from mobile connectivity. This was partially offset by a $175 million decrease in the government connectivity business.\n\nDespite rising costs, the segment's profitability improved. Connectivity income from operations increased by $155 million (15.0%) to $1,188 million, and Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA increased by $469 million to $2,087 million. Cost of revenue rose by $437 million (36.0%) primarily due to higher depreciation of capitalized launch and satellite costs, alongside increased ground operating, customer support, and international expansion expenses. R&D also grew by $82 million (66.7%) for next-generation satellite and Starlink Kit development.",
