2026-06-25 00:57:21,871 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## Implied Revenue Multiple: Starlink vs. OneWeb\n\n### Source Figures\n\n**SpaceX (S-1, Q1 2026 — three months ended March 31, 2026):**\n- Connectivity segment revenue: **$3,257 million**\n- (Up 31.6% YoY from $2,475M in Q1 2025; includes Starlink consumer subscriptions, Starlink Kit hardware sales, enterprise [aviation/maritime/land mobility], government [Starshield], and mobile connectivity)\n\n**Eutelsat (H1 FY2025-26 — six months ended December 31, 2025):**\n- LEO (OneWeb) revenue: **€110.5 million**\n- (Up ~59.7% like-for-like YoY; represents ~20% of group revenue and over one-third of Connectivity revenues)\n\n### Annualization to a Common Calendar-Year Basis\n\n| Metric | Reported | Annualization Factor | Annualized Run-Rate |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| SpaceX Connectivity (Q1 2026) | $3,257M | × 4 | **$13,028M** |\n| Eutelsat LEO/OneWeb (H1 FY25-26) | €110.5M | × 2 | **€221.0M** |\n\n### Currency Conversion (EUR → USD)\nUsing the EUR/USD spot rate at the close of Eutelsat\'s reporting period (December 31, 2025 = 1.1746):\n- €221.0M × 1.1746 = **~$259.59M**\n\n(Using the early-March 2026 rate of ~1.1759 yields ~$259.88M — immaterially different.)\n\n### Implied Revenue Multiple\n\n**$13,028M ÷ $259.59M ≈ 50.19x**\n\nEquivalently, converting SpaceX to EUR: (€2,774.1M × 4) ÷ €221M ≈ **50.19x**\n\n**Starlink\'s annualized run-rate exceeds OneWeb\'s by approximately 50x.**\n\n---\n\n### What This Reveals About Relative Commercial Maturity\n\n1. **Order-of-magnitude scale gap.** Starlink\'s connectivity business is generating revenue at roughly fifty times the rate of OneWeb. Even though OneWeb is growing faster in percentage terms (~60% vs. ~32%), the absolute dollar gap is widening, not narrowing. Starlink added ~$782M of incremental YoY quarterly revenue; OneWeb added roughly €41M of incremental semi-annual revenue (~$48M) — meaning Starlink is adding connectivity revenue at a pace roughly 30–40x faster in absolute terms.\n\n2. **Direct-to-consumer vs. wholesale architecture.** Starlink\'s scale reflects a vertically integrated, direct-to-consumer model (subscriptions + terminal hardware sales to millions of subscribers), whereas OneWeb operates primarily as a wholesale/B2B capacity provider selling to telecom partners, ISPs, governments, and enterprises. The DTC model produces far higher revenue per unit of constellation capacity because it monetizes the end-user directly rather than sharing economics with distribution partners.\n\n3. **Different points on the maturity curve.** OneWeb is still in early commercial ramp (constellation only recently completed, ~20% of group revenue, capacity-based contracts being filled). Starlink is past the inflection: it has crossed into positive segment operating income ($1,188M in Q1 2026) and Segment Adjusted EBITDA of $2,087M, indicating the business is now self-funding its growth. OneWeb\'s contribution to Eutelsat\'s adjusted EBITDA margin actually compressed group margin (52.1% vs. 55.2%) due to product-mix effects during the LEO ramp.\n\n4. **Subscriber economics vs. capacity economics.** SpaceX discloses Starlink Subscriber growth of 104.7% YoY (offset by a 22.9% ARPU decline from international/low-price-plan mix). Eutelsat\'s LEO disclosure is capacity- and contract-oriented rather than subscriber-count-oriented, reflecting the wholesale model. The two are not directly comparable on a per-customer basis.\n\n---\n\n### Disclosure Differences That Limit Precision of a Direct Comparison\n\n1. **Segment scope mismatch.** SpaceX\'s "Connectivity" segment is broad — it bundles consumer subscriptions, terminal hardware sales, enterprise mobility, government (Starshield), and mobile. Eutelsat\'s "LEO" line is narrower — it is specifically OneWeb constellation revenue, which is itself a subset of Eutelsat\'s broader "Connectivity" revenues (which also include €132.1M of GEO Fixed Connectivity). A like-for-like comparison would require stripping hardware revenue from SpaceX and adding GEO fixed connectivity to Eutelsat, neither of which is cleanly separable from the filings.\n\n2. **Fiscal-year and reporting-period misalignment.** SpaceX reports on calendar quarters (Q1 2026 = Jan–Mar 2026). Eutelsat reports on a July–June fiscal year (H1 FY2025-26 = Jul–Dec 2025). The two annualized figures therefore cover overlapping but non-identical 12-month windows, and neither captures identical seasonality.\n\n3. **Currency.** SpaceX reports in USD; Eutelsat in EUR. The ~50x multiple is robust to reasonable FX assumptions (1.17–1.18 EUR/USD), but precise comparison requires a stated conversion rate and date, which neither filing prescribes for cross-company benchmarking.\n\n4. **Annualization methodology.** Simple ×4 / ×2 multiplication assumes a flat run-rate with no intra-year growth or seasonality. Both businesses are in high-growth phases, so the annualized figures likely understate full-year actuals — and the understatement is asymmetric (Starlink\'s quarterly sequential growth trajectory is steeper in absolute dollars). The "multiple" is therefore a point-in-time run-rate snapshot, not a forecast of full-year revenue.\n\n5. **Hardware vs. service revenue split.** SpaceX\'s Connectivity includes one-time Starlink Kit (terminal) sales, which are not separately disclosed within the segment. Eutelsat\'s LEO revenue presentation does not cleanly separate hardware from service. Because hardware revenue has different unit economics and recurrence than subscription revenue, blending them complicates margin and run-rate comparisons.\n\n6. **Recast consolidated reporting (SpaceX).** SpaceX\'s S-1 financials are retrospectively recast under common-control accounting to include xAI (merged Feb 2, 2026) and X Holdings (merged into xAI Mar 28, 2025) for all historical periods. The Connectivity segment itself is SpaceX-specific and is not contaminated by the xAI/X recast, but a reader must verify that the segment figures reflect standalone SpaceX connectivity economics rather than consolidated-group allocations.\n\n7. **Growth-rate basis.** Eutelsat\'s ~60% is "like-for-like" (constant scope/perimeter). SpaceX\'s 31.6% is reported YoY on a recast basis. The two growth rates are not computed on identical methodological footings.\n\n8. **Subscriber/capacity disclosure asymmetry.** SpaceX discloses Starlink Subscriber counts and ARPU; Eutelsat discloses LEO revenue and capacity/contract milestones but not a directly comparable end-user subscriber count, making per-customer or per-unit-capacity benchmarking impossible from the filings alone.\n\n---\n\n### Bottom Line\n\nOn a like-for-like annualized run-rate basis, **Starlink\'s connectivity revenue is approximately 50x OneWeb\'s LEO revenue** (~$13.0B vs. ~$0.26B). The gap reflects not just scale but fundamentally different commercial architectures (DTC + hardware vs. wholesale capacity), different points on the maturity curve (Starlink is segment-EBITDA-positive and self-funding; OneWeb is still in early ramp and dilutive to group margin), and disclosure frameworks that are not directly reconcilable without adjustment. The ~50x figure should be read as an order-of-magnitude indicator rather than a precise like-for-like ratio.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Q1 2026 Connectivity segment revenue and MD&A"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.satellitetoday.com/finance/2026/02/13/leo-revenues-surge-for-eutelsat-operator-cancels-flexsat-geo-order",\n      "name": "Via Satellite — \'LEO Revenues Surge for Eutelsat\' (Feb 13, 2026): H1 FY2025-26 LEO revenue €110.5M, ~60% YoY growth"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.broadbandtvnews.com/2026/02/13/eutelsat-leo-revenues-jump-60",\n      "name": "Broadband TV News — \'Eutelsat LEO revenues jump 60%\' (Feb 13, 2026): LEO €110.5M, ~20% of total revenues"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://in.investing.com/news/company-news/eutelsat-h1-202526-slides-show-60-leo-revenue-growth-amid-financial-restructuring-93CH-5239064",\n      "name": "Investing.com — Eutelsat H1 2025-26 slides: LEO +59.7% like-for-like to €110.5M; adjusted EBITDA margin 52.1% vs 55.2%"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "price_history (fx: eurusd)",\n      "name": "EUR/USD historical FX rates — Dec 31, 2025 close 1.1746; Mar 1, 2026 close 1.17594"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
